{"parse":{"title":"International Book Project","pageid":20613304,"revid":755753071,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>International Book Project</b> (IBP) is a registered <a href=\"/wiki/501_(c)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"501 (c)\">501 (c)(3) not-for-profit organization</a>, founded by Harriet Van Meter in 1966, which has sent more than 6 million <a href=\"/wiki/Books\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Books\">books</a> abroad. Its mission is to promote education and <a href=\"/wiki/Literacy\" title=\"Literacy\">literacy</a> while broadening Americans' understanding of their neighbors, which it achieves by annually sending more than 200,000 books to schools, libraries, churches, and <a href=\"/wiki/Peace_Corps\" title=\"Peace Corps\">Peace Corps</a> volunteers throughout the developing world and in the United States.  The project is based in <a href=\"/wiki/Lexington,_Kentucky\" title=\"Lexington, Kentucky\">Lexington, Kentucky</a>, in a warehouse it has owned since 1983.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Mission\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Mission</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Shipping_Methods\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Shipping Methods</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Volunteer_Opportunities\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Volunteer Opportunities</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#Programs\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Programs</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#Books_Out\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Books Out</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-7\"><a href=\"#Books_as_Bridges\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4.2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Books as Bridges</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-8\"><a href=\"#Peace_Corps\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Peace Corps</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-9\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-10\"><a href=\"#Notes_and_references\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">7</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Notes and references</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=International_Book_Project&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Harriet Drury Van Meter visited <a href=\"/wiki/India\" title=\"India\">India</a> in 1965 by invitation of the <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Department_of_State\" title=\"United States Department of State\">United States Department of State</a>. While in India, she witnessed long lines of people waiting just to borrow a book to study from.  She returned to Kentucky and placed an inquiry in the English-speaking Indian newspaper <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Hindu\" title=\"The Hindu\">The Hindu</a></i>, offering books.  A large number of people responded, so Harriet Van Meter started sending books from her basement.  In 1986, Harriet Van Meter was nominated for a <a href=\"/wiki/Nobel_Peace_Prize\" title=\"Nobel Peace Prize\">Nobel Peace Prize</a> for her efforts, and she was a finalist.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In 2006, <a href=\"/wiki/Kentucky_Educational_Television\" title=\"Kentucky Educational Television\">Kentucky Educational Television</a> aired the documentary <i>Harriet Van Meter: A Life Extraordinary</i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The International Book Project has sent over 6 million books worldwide since 1966. The organization celebrated its 50th anniversary in 2016.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Mission\">Mission</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=International_Book_Project&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Mission\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>By providing needed quality books to the people of the developing world, the International Book Project seeks:\n</p>\n<ul><li>To promote education and literacy in developing countries and in areas of need within the United States</li>\n<li>To broaden Americans' understanding of their neighbors, and</li>\n<li>To foster global friendships and strengthen world unity</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Shipping_Methods\">Shipping Methods</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=International_Book_Project&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Shipping Methods\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>IBP sends books in the following ways:\n</p>\n<ul><li>Small Shipment - 35-pound boxes of books, which can be sent to anyone in the developing world with a postal address</li>\n<li>Pallet - A pallet typically contains 700 - 1,000 books. It is often sent to organizations that need more books than a small shipment can provide, but do not need or have funding for a sea container.</li>\n<li>Sea Container - 20' or 40' containers that travel by sea, containing 10,000 - 40,000 books and can stock a University library or provide textbooks for an entire school district.</li></ul>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Volunteer_Opportunities\">Volunteer Opportunities</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=International_Book_Project&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Volunteer Opportunities\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>IBP was started when volunteers started sending books from Mrs. Van Meter's basement, and IBP still needs help. IBP is a small organization, a staff of five, with just four full-time employees. \n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Programs\">Programs</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=International_Book_Project&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: Programs\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Books_Out\">Books Out</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=International_Book_Project&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: Books Out\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p><i>Books Out</i> is a self-service program in which representatives from organizations abroad or in areas of need within the United States come to select books at the IBP warehouse and deliver them personally.\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Books_as_Bridges\">Books as Bridges</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=International_Book_Project&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7\" title=\"Edit section: Books as Bridges\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p><i>Books as Bridges</i> is an international pen-pal program which partners Central Kentucky classrooms with classrooms in developing countries around the world. Through shared artwork and letters of participants, the program encourages students to develop higher reading levels, cultural awareness, and international friendships. By fostering international friendships, Books as Bridges hopes to spark a passion for social change among Central Kentucky youth.\n</p><p>The classrooms in Central Kentucky receive cultural lessons about their partner classrooms.  In the developing world, the classrooms receive a box of books as an impetus to continue in the program.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Peace_Corps\">Peace Corps</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=International_Book_Project&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8\" title=\"Edit section: Peace Corps\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>IBP often sends books to Peace Corps Volunteers.  In 1992, IBP was named \"A Partner for Peace\" by the US Peace Corps.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=International_Book_Project&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.intlbookproject.org\">International Book Project website</a></li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.peacecorps.gov\">Peace Corps website</a></li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.americorps.gov/vista\">AmeriCorps VISTA website</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes_and_references\">Notes and references</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=International_Book_Project&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10\" title=\"Edit section: Notes and references\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://askus.bloginky.com/2007/10/12/kentuckys-brush-with-nobelity/\">Lexington Herald-Leader: Kentucky's brush with Nobelity</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.ket.org/series/KHVAN/\">\"Harriet Van Meter: A Life Extraordinary\"</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Harriet+Van+Meter%3A+A+Life+Extraordinary&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ket.org%2Fseries%2FKHVAN%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AInternational+Book+Project\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.kentucky.com/news/local/news-columns-blogs/tom-eblen/article42612801.html\">\"Tom Eblen: Started in Lexington basement, International Book Project prepares to celebrate 50 years\"</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Tom+Eblen%3A+Started+in+Lexington+basement%2C+International+Book+Project+prepares+to+celebrate+50+years&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.kentucky.com%2Fnews%2Flocal%2Fnews-columns-blogs%2Ftom-eblen%2Farticle42612801.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AInternational+Book+Project\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.kentucky.com/opinion/op-ed/article100482437.html\">\"50 years ago, one Lexington woman began a global outreach\"</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=50+years+ago%2C+one+Lexington+woman+began+a+global+outreach&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.kentucky.com%2Fopinion%2Fop-ed%2Farticle100482437.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AInternational+Book+Project\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1261\nCached time: 20180910180654\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.064 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.086 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 218/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 3670/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 90/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 2982/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.024/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 1.68 MB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion t